Step 7 — Run Prisma migration on production DB
-----------------------------------------------
After first Bicep deploy, run migrations once:

  # Get DATABASE_URL from App Service config
  DATABASE_URL=$(az webapp config appsettings list \
    --resource-group servisite-rg \
    --name servisite-prod-backend \
    --query "[?name=='DATABASE_URL'].value" -o tsv)

  DATABASE_URL="$DATABASE_URL" npx prisma migrate deploy


Step 8 — DNS in IONOS (servisite.co.uk)
-----------------------------------------
Get the Front Door hostname after Bicep deploy:

  az afd endpoint show \
    --resource-group servisite-rg \
    --profile-name servisite-prod-fd \
    --endpoint-name servisite \
    --query hostName -o tsv

Add to IONOS DNS:

  Type    Name    Value
  ------  ------  ----------------------------------------
  ALIAS   @       <front-door-hostname>.azurefd.net
  CNAME   www     <front-door-hostname>.azurefd.net
  CNAME   *       <front-door-hostname>.azurefd.net  ← wildcard for tenant subdomains


Step 9 — First code deploy
----------------------------
Push to main or trigger manually:

  gh workflow run backend.yml
  gh workflow run frontend.yml

Or just push a commit — both workflows trigger automatically on changes.


Stripe webhook endpoint
------------------------
After first deploy, register the webhook in Stripe Dashboard:
  URL:    https://www.servisite.co.uk/api/v1/billing/webhook
  Events: checkout.session.completed
          customer.subscription.created
          customer.subscription.updated
          customer.subscription.deleted
          invoice.payment_succeeded
          invoice.payment_failed
          account.updated

Then copy the signing secret (whsec_...) into parameters.secrets.json
and redeploy Bicep (Step 4) so Key Vault gets the updated value.


Generate VAPID keys (one-time)
-------------------------------
  npx web-push generate-vapid-keys

Copy publicKey → vapidPublicKey in parameters.secrets.json
Copy privateKey → vapidPrivateKey in parameters.secrets.json


